    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Does white wine really pair better with seafood than red wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While white wine is traditionally preferred with seafood due to its higher acidity and lighter body that doesn't overpower delicate fish flavors, this isn't a hard rule. Light-bodied reds like Pinot Noir work beautifully with salmon or tuna, while rich shellfish dishes can handle fuller whites like oaked Chardonnay. The key is matching the wine's intensity to the preparation method and sauce rather than following rigid color rules.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with shellfish versus finfish?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Shellfish like lobster, crab, and scallops have natural sweetness and brininess that pairs excellently with crisp, mineral-driven wines like Chablis or Sancerre. Finfish varies dramatically—delicate white fish like sole needs light, citrusy wines, while meaty fish like swordfish can handle more robust wines with oak aging. The shellfish's iodine notes particularly complement wines with high minerality from coastal vineyards.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibered text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve seafood wines at a different temperature than other whites?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Seafood wines should be served slightly warmer than typical white wine service temperature—around 48-52°F rather than the standard 45°F. This slightly warmer serving temperature allows the wine's minerality and subtle fruit flavors to emerge more fully, creating better harmony with the seafood's natural salinity. Over-chilling can mute the wine's ability to complement the dish's oceanic characteristics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why do sommeliers recommend Muscadet and Albariño specifically for oysters?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Muscadet and Albariño are grown in coastal regions where the vines are influenced by ocean spray and maritime climates, creating wines with pronounced minerality and salinity. These characteristics mirror the briny, mineral qualities of oysters, creating what sommeliers call a "terroir match." Both wines also have razor-sharp acidity that cleanses the palate between each oyster, preventing flavor fatigue during a raw bar session.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for grilled seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is selecting the same delicate white wine you'd pair with poached fish when grilling adds smoky, caramelized flavors that need a more robust wine. Grilled seafood requires wines with more body and complexity—think oaked Chardonnay, Viognier, or even light reds like Pinot Noir. The char and grill marks create entirely new flavor compounds that delicate wines simply can't match.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good budget alternatives to expensive Sancerre and Chablis for seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—look for Muscadet from France (often under $15), Portuguese Vinho Verde, or Spanish Rías Baixas Albariño for exceptional seafood wines under $20. From the New World, try Sauvignon Blanc from Chile's Casablanca Valley or unoaked Chardonnay from Australia's Adelaide Hills. These wines offer similar crisp acidity and mineral characteristics at a fraction of the cost of prestigious Burgundy or Loire Valley bottles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does the sauce or preparation method change my wine choice for seafood?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The sauce is often more important than the seafood itself when selecting wine. Creamy sauces call for richer whites like Chardonnay or white Rhône blends, while tomato-based sauces work better with rosé or light reds due to their acidity. Asian preparations with ginger and soy need aromatic wines like Riesling or Gewürztraminer, while simple lemon and herb preparations showcase mineral-driven wines like Sancerre perfectly.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can sparkling wine work with seafood beyond just oysters?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling wine is incredibly versatile with seafood beyond the classic oyster pairing. Champagne and Cava work beautifully with fried seafood as the bubbles and acidity cut through oil, while Prosecco complements light seafood salads and crudo preparations. The key is matching the sparkling wine's style to the dish—lean, mineral sparklers for raw preparations, and richer, yeastier styles for cooked seafood with cream sauces.</p>
  </div>
